long_desc.thetext: I confirm the bug. It is odd luxrender tried to use qt5. I posted the issue to upstream and see what they can find http://www.luxrender.net/forum/viewtopic.php?f=21&t=13248

Created attachment 1242023 ldd-luxrender
With help from upstream, it seems something is wrong with qt configuration within Fedora thus beyond my skills. I include ldd luxrender result showing the correct association with qt4.

$ env LANG=en_US.utf8 yum-deprecated remove qt5-qtbase Resolving Dependencies --> Running transaction check ---> Package qt5-qtbase.x86_64 0:5.7.1-10.fc25 will be erased --> Processing Dependency: libQt5Core.so.5()(64bit) for package: opencv-core-3.1.0-8.fc25.x86_64 --> Processing Dependency: libQt5Core.so.5(Qt_5)(64bit) for package: opencv-core-3.1.0-8.fc25.x86_64 ......
--> Running transaction check ---> Package opencv-core.x86_64 0:3.1.0-8.fc25 will be erased --> Processing Dependency: libopencv_core.so.3.1()(64bit) for package: OpenImageIO-1.6.16-1.fc25.x86_64 --> Processing Dependency: libopencv_highgui.so.3.1()(64bit) for package: OpenImageIO-1.6.16-1.fc25.x86_64 --> Processing Dependency: libopencv_videoio.so.3.1()(64bit) for package: OpenImageIO-1.6.16-1.fc25.x86_64
--> Running transaction check ---> Package OpenImageIO.x86_64 0:1.6.16-1.fc25 will be erased --> Processing Dependency: libOpenImageIO.so.1.6()(64bit) for package: LuxRender-lib-1.6-4.fc25.x86_64 --> Processing Dependency: libOpenImageIO.so.1.6()(64bit) for package: LuxRender-core-1.6-4.fc25.x86_64 --> Processing Dependency: libOpenImageIO.so.1.6()(64bit) for package: LuxRender-1.6-4.fc25.x86_64
--> Running transaction check ---> Package LuxRender.x86_64 0:1.6-4.fc25 will be erased ---> Package LuxRender-core.x86_64 0:1.6-4.fc25 will be erased ---> Package LuxRender-lib.x86_64 0:1.6-4.fc25 will be erased

Maybe the easiest way is to ask OpenImageIO maintainer to create another library without using opencv, put such library into some non-standard directory, and make LuxRender use such OpenImageIO library??

(In reply to Mamoru TASAKA from comment #4) > Maybe the easiest way is to ask OpenImageIO maintainer to create another > library without using opencv, put such library into some non-standard > directory, and make LuxRender use such OpenImageIO library??
Actually, it appears that the libOpenImageIO.so.1.6 -> libopencv_highgui.so.3.1 may not be strictly necessary; the OpenCV APIs used by OpenImageIO were in the highgui library prior to 3.0, but are now in the videoio library (which does not depend on Qt). Dropping that DT_NEEDED would clean up this issue without losing functionality.
I started working on some patches for OpenImageIO to do that, but I need to go AFK for a few hours.
